                    <div class="showPanel" id="watt_utilities-pane">
                        <p class="experienceTitle">Mid-level Developer @<span> Watt Utilities</span></p>
                        <p class="experienceDate">June 2017 - February 2019</p>
                        <ul>
                            <p class="details mb-3">
                                During my time at Watt Utilities, I headed up and re-created their existing CRM system.
                                The end goal was to create a faster, more user friendly system that had a bunch of extra
                                features that were planned in the development roadmap.
                            </p>
                            <p class="details mb-3">
                                I started out by taking the current system and finding out what was broken, slow and
                                didn't work the way it was expected to. Next, I asked the in-house sales staff what parts
                                weren't working for them (e.g anything that made their jobs slow or more painful). After
                                I was able to find out what was bad, I logged all the other parts and classed those bits
                                as 'good code'.
                            </p>
                            <p class="details mb-3">
                                After I was able to determine what was good and bad code, I replicated the codebase and
                                stripped out everything that was bad. I made a new GitHub repository and stored the initial
                                commit in there. Next, I sat with my manager and discussed a few points to work on including;
                                system account security, refactoring useless site-wide code, a sub-roadmap for where the new
                                features would be implemented and how the implementation would be performed.
                            </p>
                            <p class="details">
                                After 1 year and 9 months of development, the new CRM system was complete with a bunch of new
                                features, enhanced performance and overall better user experience. Needless to say, the sales
                                staff loved it. There was plans for me to stay with Watt Utilities but other commitments
                                made this impossible.
                            </p>
                        </ul>
